
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `ddstdecode` baraye baz kardane file-haye `.dds` (DirectDraw Surface) estefade mishavad va anha ra be format-haye dige mesle `.png` ya `.bmp` tabdil mikonad. In dastoor bishtar baraye kasani ke ba grafic va bazi-sazi kar mikonan mofid ast.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `ddstdecode input.dds output.png` --> 🖼️ Tabdil file `.dds` be `.png`. Agar `output.png` vojood nadashte bashad, yek file jadid dorost mikonad.
    🔹 `ddstdecode input.dds` --> 🖼️ Tabdil file `.dds` be `.bmp` ba hamin name dar haman directory. Agar name file kharoji ra moshakhas nakonid, be soorate pishfarz be `.bmp` tabdil mishavad.
    🔹 `ddstdecode -r input.dds` --> 🔄 Bargardandan rang-ha (red and blue channels). In gozine vaghti be kar miayad ke rang-haye tasvir dar format `.dds` ghalat namayesh dade shavand.
    🔹 `ddstdecode -m` --> ℹ️ Namayesh etela'at bishtar dar morede file `.dds` be jaye tabdil an.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ ddstdecode texture.dds texture.png

    🔹 Tabdil `texture.dds` be `texture.png`.

    $ ddstdecode model.dds

    🔹 Tabdil `model.dds` be `model.bmp`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ ddstdecode icon.dds icon.png

    🔹 File `icon.dds` ra be `icon.png` tabdil mikonad. Agar icon.png dar hale hazer vojood nadashte bashad, dastoor `ddstdecode` yek file jadid ba name `icon.png` misazad va tasvir ra dar an zakhire mikonad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `ddstdecode` command is used to decode `.dds` (DirectDraw Surface) files and convert them to other image formats like `.png` or `.bmp`. This command is especially useful for those working with graphics and game development.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `ddstdecode input.dds output.png` --> 🖼️ Convert the `.dds` file to `.png`.  If `output.png` does not exist, it will create a new file.
    🔹 `ddstdecode input.dds` --> 🖼️ Convert the `.dds` file to `.bmp` with the same name in the same directory. If you don't specify an output filename, it defaults to `.bmp`.
    🔹 `ddstdecode -r input.dds` --> 🔄 Reverse the red and blue channels.  This option is useful if the colors in the `.dds` image are displayed incorrectly.
    🔹 `ddstdecode -m` --> ℹ️ Show more information about the `.dds` file instead of converting it.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ ddstdecode texture.dds texture.png

    🔹 Converts `texture.dds` to `texture.png`.

    $ ddstdecode model.dds

    🔹 Converts `model.dds` to `model.bmp`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ ddstdecode icon.dds icon.png

    🔹 Converts the file `icon.dds` to `icon.png`. If `icon.png` does not currently exist, the `ddstdecode` command will create a new file named `icon.png` and store the image in it.
